\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid15214360\contextualspace \rtlch\fcs1 \af31507\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15214360 BEAUTIFUL SANTA BARBARA AN OUT-OF-DOOR PARADISE
\par 
\par It Is the Riviera of the Great Pacific Coast, and Was Named For a Girl Killed By Her Father&#8212;Daughter of a Roman General Who Perished a Christian Martyr&#8212;California Found in 1542, and Explored 
Just Fifty Years After Columbus Discovered America&#8212;Santa Barbara Is the Place Where Tired People Come to Soak Up Sunshine&#8212;It Is Rich, But Democratic&#8212A Single Grapevine Covers an Acre, Produces Ten Tons of Grapes, Is Eight Feet in Circumfe
rence at the Base&#8212;Walnuts Yield $200 or More to the Acre.
\par Editor Telegram:
\par 
\par Please inform us how California compares in size with Pennsylvania?
\par 
\par Ans.&#8212;There cannot be a comparison. California has 99,463,681 acres. To get a comparative idea you ca
n take the states of Maine, Vermont, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland, and spreading them all out together over California there would be an uncovered margin of 13,774 squar
e miles, or more than enough in excess to make mroe than ten states like Rhode Island. California is "some" state.
\par 
\par NUMBER VII.
\par 
\par There is more than one outdoor paradise in California. In the list do not fail to include Santa Barbara. The climate has attract
ed invalids and persons in search of health and pleasure since the earliest settlement of the Pacific coast. While California was still a part of Mexico, many refined and aristocratic Spanish families made it their home and contributed to the charm of soc
ial life. A few descendants of the early Spanish settlers still reside there. They have become thoroughly Americanized, but may easily be identified by their names, their features and complexions and the graceful manners of their race.
\par 
\par The mission of Santa Barbara is the best preserved in California, its monastery is the most extensive, it is an educational institution of high standard, and its influence is the widest of any in the state.
\par 
\par Many people consider Santa Barbara the most desirable place of resid
ence for families of wealth and leisure in the United States, if not in the world. The climate and environment are very much like those of the Riviera of France. It is the only place of resort in the United States which has a mountain range on one side of
 
it, and an ocean on the other, and where the climate permits the population to live in comfort the year around. It is often called the Newport of the Pacific, but is more democratic and cosmopolitan than the queen of the Atlanic resorts. No social tyranny
 
is recognized; the habits and customs of the people are not so artificial; everybody lives as nearly as possible to nature:[;] there is no rivalry in dress or dinner parties, or other forms of display; all classes spend most of their time out-of-doors, an
d
 the belle of Santa Barbara shows to the best advantage in a Khaki suit, astride a mustang climbing a mountain trail, rather than at a ball or garden party. The population is made up mostly of "remitters"&#8212;that is in this instance people who have ret
i
red from business, widows of large means, and others who are able to live luxuriously upon the proceeds of investments elsewhere. Many people from San Francisco spent part of the winters in Santa Barbara, owning or renting bungalows, which are of all size
s. There are colonies of people from the big eastern cities of Boston and New York.. The richest resident is a petroleum prince, who has figured in the divorce courts.
\par 
\par Between the mission and the sea runs the main street of the town, a wide, well-paved tho
roughfare, more than two miles long, which is lined on both sides with business blocks, banks, mercantile establishments, and the best bookstores and curio shops to be found on the Pacific coast. The high class of goods they keep is an index to the wealth
 
and culture of the community. There is a line of trolley cars running from the beach to the mission[,] and a wide and beautiful boulevard follows the shore line for several miles. At the northern end are bath houses, and a bathing pier near a plaza, where
 
a band plays every afternoon. There is sea bathing the year round, and one of the finest bath houses in the land. There are several sanitariums and hot medicinal springs at an elevation of 1,300 feet. One may spend an entire winter in Santa Barbara, and f
ollow a different drive or trail every day.
\par 
\par In fact, no city in California has so many beautiful drives and trails for motors, carriages and saddle horses. The Santa Ynez range of mountains is broken by innumerable canyons and gorges, and between them lie 
broad table lands, which are occupied as ranches, olive groves and walnut orchards. There is a drive or a trail through every canyon, and one of them known as La Cumbre trail, twelve miles long, offers a continuous panorama of glorious scenery. It crosses
 
the mountains through a pass a little less than 4,000 feet above the seas. Another trail reaches the summit of the range by a climb of twelve to fourteen miles, and is equally attractive. The lowest pass is 2,224 feet, but it is possible to climb nearly 8
,000[,] either on horseback or by motor.
\par 
\par In Santa Barbara there is no rivalry in architecture or extravagance. The great competition is in flowers, plants and vegetable gardens. Most of the residences are of the villa type, simple and often severe. The ide
al house is of shingles, stained brown, with wide porches hidden by climbing roses and other vines and furnished with hammocks and easy chairs. The fact that the temperature rarely varies more than twelve to fifteen degrees from one year's end to another,
 
and is always moderatley warm, enables everybody to live in the open air, and is, of course, a blessing to the infirm and weary, and has a wholesome influence. People from the east go to Santa Barbara to be soaked in sunshine, and play golf 365 days in th
e
 year. The villa population is quite exclusive and has a society of its own. During the winter season the two great hotels, the Potter, probably as large as the largest on the coast, and one of the finest, and the Arlington, which has recently been erecte
d
 upon the site of an old house of the same name, are filled with eastern people. During the summer middle west and western people take advantage at the hotels of the lower rates. The Potter hotel is very close to the ocean, where the sea bathers revel, an
d the great lawn on that side is in fact a perfect ocean of flowers.
\par 
\par The Arlington hotel is also attractive. It belongs to E. P. Ripley, president of the Santa Fe railroad, and he is the man who controlled the contracting company which built the Lackawanna
 railroad from Binghamton to Buffalo about 1880. One of his subcontractors was the late John B. McDonald, who made fame and wealth as the builder of the New York city subway. Mr. Ripley in 1880, was in a way, Mr. McDonald's financial backer. The writer sa
w
 Mr. Ripley recently in Santa Barbara, and he looks almost as strong as he did over thirty years ago. His hotel is built of concrete and steel[,] and is after the mission style of architecture, has 300 rooms and cost nearly a half million dollars. The mis
s
ion idea is carried out in every room and corridor, the woodwork being left in the rough and stained a dark brown by the use of petroleum. There are no ceilings. The heavy rafters are left uncovered; the walls are rough plaster, painted to match the woodw
ork; the floors are red tiles and even the bath tubs are of mission design.
\par 
\par The mission style of architecture with its strong but simples [sic] lines, Moors and introduced into Mexico, was used by the Franciscan missionaries because they found it the best 
suited to the climate. That was the reason it was adopted in the south of Spain. The brick and tile did not reflect, but absorbed the glare of the sun. The cloisters are cool at noonday and the thick walls are proof agianst the dampness of the rainy seaso
n
. It is being used more and more for public buildings, school houses, hotels, and nearly all the new schools and public edifices are being built after the mision design. The government architects planned the conventional granite for the federal post-offic
e at Riverside, Cal., but to the end that a harmonious architectrure should prevail in the city, President Taft directed that the Riverside post-office should conform to the mission style.
\par 
\par All about Santa Barabara is attractive. The entire amphitheater inc
losed by the Santa Ynez mountains on the one side and the Pacific ocean on the other, is entirely taken up by rich ranchmen, who own large estates and keep most of their lands in natural parks. They visit in automobiles and on horseback; they wear sombrer
o
s and comfortable clothing; they take pride in their crops and orchards and brag about their walnuts and their olives. This is the walnut country par excellence, and it is the best paying crop. The trees require ten years to mature, but give no further tr
o
uble. It is only necessary to keep down the weeds and loosen the surface of the soil with plow and harrow. Walnut trees are not subject to diseases like fruit trees. The nuts require no refrigeration, cannot spoil on the hands of the grower, and sell for 
n
ot less than twelve cents a pound on the cars. The average profit to the grower is $200 an acre. Walnut orchards are mostly limited in area. The largest in California has only 350 acres, and most of them are of less than twenty acres. But the business is 
extending rapidly.
\par 
\par The walnut acreage will soon be increased when the entire Golita
 valley is irrigated. Irrigation will enable the farmers to extend the walnut and lemon groves and grow more beans, for these three are great staples. Santa Barbara has been boring a hold through the Santa Ynez range of mountains for a large and permanent
 
water supply. The tunnel is seven by nine feet in size and 7,000 feet through the mountain. Aqueducts were designed for both sides and the aqueducts' supply of water for drinking, irrigation, etc., will be enough for a population of 250,000 people. No one
 dreams that Santa Barbara will ever have such a population. The new scheme is to irrigate the Golita valley.
\par 
\par Writing of lemons, it is worth mention that the Crocker family have an enormous lemon ranch in the Montecito valley, just over a ridge from Santa 
Barbara, with a large stone packing house and all the appurtenances and ship their crops by the train load. It is the most extensive and complete lemon ranch in America, with 2,000 acres of trees. The crops are truly wonderful. In this temperature, and in
 
a soil of surpassing richness, everything grows. All the plants known to the temperature and semi-temperate regions live happily together. The palm and the pine, the apple and the oleander[,] the maple and the magnolia grow side by side with equal vigor. 
R
oses bloom and strawberry beds give ripened fruit every month. The cultivation of vegetables and small fruits for the local market, is the most profitable kind of farming, however, as hotels and boarding houses consume large quantities of both. The cultiv
a
tion of flowers and plants is also a profitable business. On the main street of Santa Barbara is a concern which imports shrubs, vines, plants and trees from everywhere and acclimates them for California. You can see nearly a half hundred kinds of palms, 
camphor and cinnamon trees, papyrus, bamboos of all sorts and sizes, hibiscus, agavas, bread-fruit, and other strange plants that you read about in Robinson Crusoe, the Swiss Family Robinson and other tales of the South Sea islands.
\par 
\par Out in Montecito park a
n oil and steel magnate named Gillespie has a great show place. It took eight years to construct the palace and surroundings at a cost of more than $3,000,000. It is first of all a palm park. But it is more. The home is copied after some Roman villa, and 
t
he grounds likewise. This palace and palm park is open to visitors at certain hours each day when Mr. Gillespie is away. The house has a great plunge like to the Roman baths. The water runs into high reservoirs, which as they are located along the descend
i
ng hillside in front are tapped by pipes from which the palms are watered. Mr. Gillespie has been traveling the world over for many years looking for new varieties of palms[.] He now has about eighty distinct varieties and has sold single plants for as mu
ch as $500. A Buffalo man, the head of the Pierce-Arrow Automobile company, occupies the palace this winter. 
\par 
\par Some of the finest grapes in California are grown about Santa Barbara the vines having been imported from Spain in the early days by the Francisca
n fathers who taught the natives how to make wine as well as olive oil. The largest grape vine in the world, it is said, grows in Carpinter\'ed
a valley, a few miles from Santa Barbara. It was planted in 1843 by a Spanish farmer and has yielded ten tons of gra
pes in a single season. It spreads over an acre of ground and is supported by seventy-eight posts. If it were not pruned so closely every season it would cover a much larger area. Six inches from the ground the trunk measures eight and one-half feet in ci
r
cumference, and where it reaches the trellis and begins to spread, about six and one-half feet from the ground, the girth is five feet seven inches. There are several other very large vines int he same neighborhood. One of the largest ever known was cut d
own and sent to the Philadelphia centennial exposition in 1876, as a sample of California products and was a great advertisment for the state.
\par 
\par It will be of interest to all who love the words and music of the song "The Rosary," to know the words were writt
en in Santa Barbara by Cameron Rogers. He is an artist; he lives there and from his studio window there is a most entrancing view. It was set to music by Ethelbert Nevin. Nearby to the scenes of beauty in Santa Barbara one can find the greasy conditions o
f
 a rich oil country. Crude petroleum gushes up from the earth and sea at Summerland, a town near Santa Barbara. It is occupied by a colony of Spiritualists. It looks like one of the old fashioned oil towns of Pennsylvania. The first petroleum was discover
e
d on the hillside, and the veins were followed down to the ocean, where what the Californians call "submarine wells" have been bo[r]ed and piped and are now flowing regularly. The oil comes up first through the sand, and then piped through the water and t
h
ence to the reservoirs on shore. The people of Summerland were the first to discover the adaptability of crude petroleum for making roads. It was an accident. The first man to use the crude petroleum on a road was so lazy that he shoveled the refuse from 
a
n oil tank into the street to get rid of it, when he should have carted it off to some dumping ground. The oil immediately absorbed the dust, and the heavy metal wheels which passed over it packed it down into a hard, smooth surface like asphaltum which s
hed the rains and was never muddy or dusty. His neighbors then put oil on the roadways in front of their houses to keep down the dust, and the practice finally became general and is now used effectively in every part of the country[.]
\par 
\par The history of Santa 
Barbara is very romantic, but the town acquired its name from a tragedy, due to a father's killing of his daughter, and after her it was named. Santa Barbara was one of the early martyrs. She was born in Asia Minor, and was the daughter of a Roman general
.
 She was convereted to Christianity when she was sixteen years old, in the year A. D. 233, during the reign of Alexander Severus, an emperor frindly to the Christians. His successor, Maximinus, was a thorough pagan and ordered all Christian converts put t
o
 death. The father of Barbara was Deoscorus, and he concealed her, hoping to persuade her to recant. When he was unable to do so he inflicted upon her cruel torments, which she bore with wonderful fortitude for a girl of seventeen, and he finally slew her
 
with his own hand. Her piety, her steadfastness for the faith, and her example had great influence with the young Christians and caused her to be canonized by both the Greek and Roman Catholic churches. She suffered martyrdom at Nocomedia, Asia Minor abou
t 235 A. D. It was not by a monk that Santa Barbara was named but by a Portuguese explorer, as will later apear.
\par 
\par Off the coast of Santa Barbara is an archipelago of mountainous islands, the largest being called San Miguel, Santa Rosa and Santa Cruz. When t
he Spaniards first discovered the country they were all inhabited, but after the mission was established the island families were persuaded by the friars to move over to the mainland and settle near by. Juan Rodnguez [Rodr\'ed
guez] Cabrillo, the discoverer of
 California, is buried upon the island of San Miguel, although no trace of his grave remains. He was the first European who is known to have explored the Pacific coast of what is now the United States. He was a navigator of enterprise, courage and tact, a
nd although a Portuguese by birth, spent most of his life in the service of Spain like Columbus and Americus Vespucci, who were Italians.
\par 
\par About the middle of October 1542, just fifty years after Columbus discovered America, Cabrillo landed on the beach of 
what is now Santa Barbara, and was met by natives in their canoes, who received him with demonstrations of curiosity and kindness, and exchanged presents with him. He remained some time, exploring the surrounding country, which in his reports to the vicer
o
y of Mexico was described as of great attractiveness and fertility. He crossed to the islands of Santa Rosa, Santa Cruz and San Miguel and made the latter his headquarters, while he continued his explorations northward to a point many leagues north of the
 
bay of San Francisco, although he never found the Golden Gate. It is difficult to determine how far north he went, but we know from his narratives that he was driven back by bad weather and returned to San Miguel to recover from a fracture of his right ar
m, but he grew worse instead of better and on January 8, 1543, he died and was buried on that island.
\par 
\par Santa Barbara was given its name by Sebastian Viscaino, another Portuguese epxlorer, who set sail from Acapulco with three large caravels and a transport,
 carrying 200 soldiers and three Carmelite friars. Antonio de la Ascension, one of the friars, took copious notes of all they saw and heard along the coast, made a map of considerable detail and as directed by the explorer named each bay, cape, island and
 
other conspicuous landmark after the particular saint whose festival occurred nearest to the day of discovery. On December 4, 1602, the party landed at Santa Barbara, and that being the anniversary of Santa Barbara, her name was given to the bay and the c
ountry that surrounds it.
\par 
\par Although Viscaino was not the first discoverer of California, his voyage was the most important because of the maps  of the coast and the authentic information which Padre Antonio and the other friars were able to furnish Europe i
n regard to that part of the world. The island of Santa Cruz recieved its name from the fact that one of the early explorers lost there a crucifix of great sanctity, which was found by the natives and restored as the vessel was about to sail. 
{\*\atrfstart 481841022}A romantic na
rrative relates how in 18[5]1 George Nidever, a ranchero, of Santa Barbara, found human footprints upon the sandy beach of the island of St. Nichalas, close to Santa Cruz, which was supposed to be uninhabited. He was reminded of a story that had been wide
l
y circulated about an Indian woman who had been abandoned there and made a thorough search. On the first day he wa unsuccessful; on the second day he found evidences of human existence, including a basket rudely made of reeds; on the [third] day he found 
three small huts [made] of the ribs of a whale and cove[red] with brush. In one of these huts [was] an Indian woman, with long hair fa[ll]ing over her bare shoulders, and we[ar]ing a single garmet made of [the] skins of birds. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
