\par 
\par Until the discovery of gold in [Cal]ifornia, and the rapid development [of] San Francisco, Sacramento and o[ther] places farther north Santa Bar[bara] was s
econd only in importance [to] Monterey, on the coast. The terr[...] occupied by the missionaries [was] divided into four districts, in each [...] which was a presido, or military [p]rison, and the officers exercised [...] civil and military jurisdiction. 
[
Mon]terey was the official seat of the [gov]ernor, and the commandant at S[anta] Barbara was second in author[ity.] Thus it happend that after the d[eath] of Governor Arrellago, in 182[5, ...] Captain Arguello, commandant [of] Santa Barbara, exercised aut
h
ority [un]til a new governor arrived. After [the] Mexican war Arguello remained [at] Santa Barbara, and became one of [the] most influential men of Cal[ifornia,] where he resided for thirty-four y[ears.] Another important commander [...] Santa Barbara was
 Lieutenant [...]mundo Pacheco, and of a promin[ent] family. He left a son, Romualdo, [who] became governor of the state, and [a] member of the house of repre[senta]tives. His family still reside in [the] neighborhood.
\par 
\par At the time of the arrival of Ca[ptai
n] John C. Fremont and his little [...] in 1846, Lieutenant Raimundo Ca[...] was commander at the presidio, [and] the misssion and the property [which] surrounded it were held by Nichola[s ...] Den and Daniel Hill, two Ameri[cans] under a lease from the M
e
xican [... gov]ernment for a yearly rental of $1,[...] The lease covered all the lands [...] buildings of the missionary except [the] church and the monastery. Some li[...] head of cattle, 1,700 head of sheep [...] many horses were also included. [The] bi
shop of the California diocese [en]deavored in vain to resist the a[...] of the government, and his death [was] hastened by his failure. He died [in] 1846 and is buried in the Mi[ssion] church.
\par 
\par Daniel Hill, the lessee, was a [Cape] Cod sea captain who first visited [the] coast in command of a trading ve[ssel] in 1822, en route to the Haw[aiian] Islands, and was so much taken [with] the climate and surroundings of S[anta] Barbara, that he brought
 
his [wife] and family and settled there in 1[...] starting a trading store, bought [...] and cattle and became the richest [man] in the community. Nicholas A. [...] an Irish physician, married H[ill's] daughter. He arrived in 1836 and [prac]ticed medicine
 while he raised ca[ttle.] Before his death he, too, had be[come] very rich and was the owner of [...] large ranches as well as 10,000 ca[ttle.]
\par 
\par Several of the residences of [the] Spanish and Mexican colonial p[...] are still standing, although they [have]
 been considerably altered on mo[...] lines. The best description of life [in] Santa Barbara at that period may [be] found in Dana's "Two Years Be[fore] the Mast," which in the days of [...] youth was a universally popular [...] 
